ENG
[{'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "Germany, let's coordinate precisely: I will move F ENG to BEL this spring with A HOL supporting from your side - that guarantees Belgium falls to one of us. I propose you support F ENG into BEL with A HOL (A HOL S F ENG - BEL), and in return I'll support A HOL to hold against any French pressure. This is cleaner than both of us moving to BEL and risking a bounce. France has offered to cede BEL to me if I keep F ENG out of the Channel permanently - I'm not taking that deal, but it tells me they're nervous. Let's press the advantage together. Confirm you'll support F ENG into BEL."}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, I've considered your offer carefully. I'm willing to accept Belgium in exchange for keeping F ENG away from Brest - that's a fair trade. Move A BUR to MUN or RUH as you suggested, and I'll ensure no English fleet threatens your Atlantic coast this year. Germany is indeed the growing threat with 5 centers, and I'd rather we coordinate against them than bleed each other over BEL. If you move A BUR away from BEL this spring, I'll take BEL cleanly and we can discuss joint pressure on Germany next season. Do we have a deal?"}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, I appreciate your transparency. F NWY will move toward STP this spring - I want to be clear this is about positioning, not an immediate attack. If you'd prefer to negotiate STP's future, I'm open to a deal where you cede STP in exchange for English support against Turkey or Austria in the south. Otherwise, expect pressure from the north. Your call - let's talk terms rather than fight over it."}]
--------------
FRA
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': "England, I accept your proposal in principle — Belgium goes to you, and I will move A BUR away from BEL this spring. In return, I require your firm commitment: F ENG stays out of the Channel and away from Brest, and we coordinate against Germany's growing dominance. Germany now has 5 centers and is moving A HOL to BEL as well — they are the threat, not France. I am moving A BUR toward RUH to pressure Germany from the west. Let us build this partnership on concrete action: you take BEL, I pressure Germany, and we divide the continent between us."}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "Germany, I have decided to move A BUR to RUH this spring — not BEL. I am not contesting Belgium with you. However, I want something in return for this goodwill: acknowledge France's sphere in the west and keep your armies east of the Rhine. England is offering me an alliance against you — I am choosing to decline it for now, but that calculus changes if Germany expands aggressively toward France. Let us formalize a non-aggression pact through 1903 and focus our respective energies elsewhere."}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, Germany is the power to watch — 5 centers already and growing. I am repositioning A BUR toward RUH to apply pressure from the west. If you can move forces toward Tyrolia or threaten Munich from the south, we can squeeze Germany between us and prevent them from becoming the dominant land power. I will keep my forces away from your sphere entirely. This is the moment to act before Germany consolidates further — are you willing to coordinate a joint pressure campaign against them in 1902?'}]
--------------
ITA
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, I appreciate your directness and confirm our non-aggression pact is solid. My A TUS will move to VEN this season to consolidate my northern position, and A ROM will hold - neither threatens TRI or TYR. I'm watching Turkey's expansion with concern; they now hold GRE and BUL and their fleet in BLA gives them significant reach. When you're ready to push south against Turkey, I can coordinate from the Adriatic and Ionian. For now, let's both expand in our respective directions and keep this border quiet."}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Turkey, I appreciate the transparency. I agree Russia's 6 centers is alarming - they're the biggest threat on the board. My moves this season keep me positioned in the central Mediterranean. I have no plans toward GRE or the Aegean this season - you have my word. However, I'd caution you: Austria has units in ALB and SER that could threaten your Balkan position. If Austria pushes south, I could apply pressure from the Adriatic to relieve you. Keep me informed of Russian movements and we can coordinate accordingly."}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, agreed on all counts - A TUS will not approach PIE or MAR. I'm moving to consolidate my Adriatic position this season. On Germany: they're at 5 centers and growing fast - HOL, DEN, and a strong army position. I strongly encourage you to push toward BEL and MUN before they become unstoppable. I can apply diplomatic pressure on Germany from the south and potentially coordinate with Russia against them. England also looks to be a natural ally for you against German naval dominance - worth exploring."}]
--------------
RUS
[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Comrade, I must clarify a serious misunderstanding: A SEV did NOT move to ARM last fall - check the game record. A SEV moved to MOS, not ARM. There is no Russian army in ARM. Your intelligence is wrong. I have honored every commitment to you. F RUM is moving to BUL this spring to take that neutral center - this is not a threat to you, it is expansion at nobody's expense. F BLA should hold or support my move into BUL. Do not let a false report push you into war with Russia when we have a profitable arrangement. I am not your enemy."}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, I appreciate your candor. Turkey's message to me was based on false intelligence - they claimed I moved to ARM, which never happened. Turkey is trying to manufacture a conflict. I am taking BUL with F RUM this spring - this is my move and I will not cede RUM to you. However, I propose a clean division: I hold BUL and RUM, you hold SER and push toward GRE if Turkey weakens. GAL remains a buffer zone - neither of us enters. Turkey is the real threat to both of us in the Balkans. Let us coordinate against them rather than squabble over scraps."}, {'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'England, I must be direct: F NWY moving to STP is unacceptable and will be treated as an act of war. STP is a Russian home center. I have respected your hold on NWY without contest - I expect the same respect for my home territories. If you move on STP, I will dedicate northern resources to pushing you back and you will find Russia a determined enemy. There is no need for conflict between us - you have NWY, I have SWE, this is a stable and profitable arrangement. Do not throw away a good relationship for an aggressive gamble.'}]
--------------
AUT
[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Excellent - we are aligned. My plan this spring: F ALB moves to GRE (I need you to vacate GRE by moving A GRE -> BUL, which secures that center for you), and A SER -> BUL or holds to support. If you move A GRE -> BUL and F BLA -> RUM, I will move A SER -> RUM simultaneously - we dislodge the Russian fleet together and split the gains. I take RUM, you secure BUL. This cripples Russia immediately. Confirm you will move A GRE -> BUL so F ALB can take GRE, and F BLA -> RUM to coordinate the attack. This is our moment.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, I must warn you directly: Turkey is planning to attack RUM with F BLA this spring, and I cannot stop them - in fact I have no reason to, as BUL is the center I care about. If you want to preserve F RUM, move it to BUL/EC or SEV now before Turkey strikes. I am willing to guarantee I will NOT move A SER into RUM if you retreat F RUM to SEV peacefully - this gives you a clean withdrawal and preserves our relationship. In exchange, I ask only that you acknowledge my claim to BUL. Do not let Turkey take RUM - it will make them too strong and threaten us both.'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, I confirm our non-aggression holds. A TYR moves to VIE this spring - completely away from you. F ALB moves south toward GRE. I have no designs on VEN. Regarding Turkey: I agree they are a long-term threat, but the timing is not right for joint action yet - let me consolidate the Balkans first and then we can discuss coordinated pressure on GRE and BUL. For now, keep A TUS away from PIE and we have nothing to worry about between us.'}]
--------------
TUR
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, I've considered carefully. Russia is proposing F RUM -> BUL this spring, which would steal a center I intend to take. This confirms Russia is our common enemy. Here is my concrete proposal: I move F BLA -> RUM to dislodge the Russian fleet, while you move A SER to support F BLA -> RUM or advance toward BUL yourself. A GRE holds or moves to BUL depending on what you do. If we coordinate this correctly, Russia loses RUM and is pushed back significantly. I need to know: will you move A SER -> RUM to support my F BLA attack, or do you prefer A SER -> BUL? Either works for me - just confirm so I can issue matching orders. This is the moment to cripple Russia together."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, I have received your proposal and I must decline. F RUM moving to BUL is unacceptable - BUL is within my sphere and I will contest any Russian presence there. Furthermore, ARM remains a threat to ANK that I cannot tolerate. I am moving F BLA -> RUM this spring to remove your fleet from that position. If you wish to avoid escalation, withdraw F RUM to SEV and keep ARM out of the picture - then we can discuss a new arrangement. Otherwise, consider this the beginning of open conflict. I have coordinated with Austria accordingly.'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy, Russia is attempting to grab BUL this spring with F RUM, which threatens both our spheres. I am moving aggressively against Russia - F BLA -> RUM, coordinated with Austria. I need you to hold your current position and ensure no Austrian units threaten GRE while I'm focused north. If you can position F TUN toward ION as a show of force to keep Austria honest, that would be valuable. Our non-aggression holds firm - I simply ask you keep pressure on Austria's southern flank so they remain committed to the anti-Russia push rather than turning on me."}]
--------------
GER
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'England, we are aligned. My orders this spring: A HOL -> BEL. I will keep F DEN out of NTH and SKA as you requested - you have full freedom of movement northward. F ENG -> BEL will collide with my A HOL -> BEL, so I ask you redirect F ENG elsewhere - perhaps toward MAO or to support NWY movements. Let me take BEL with A HOL while you push north toward STP. France is the target: once I hold BEL, I can press PAR from the north while you threaten BRE from the sea. This is the squeeze that wins the west.'}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, I hear your concern about England and I share it - four centers and a fleet in the Channel is dangerous. Here is my honest assessment: if you move A BUR -> BEL, we collide and England benefits from our mutual weakness. Instead, hold BUR as the buffer you describe, and let me take BEL. Once I hold BEL, I become a land barrier between England and France, not a threat to you. My army in BEL faces England, not Paris. England's naval dominance is the real problem - I propose we each expand at England's expense rather than each other's. Keep BUR, I take BEL, and we discuss coordinating against English positions next fall."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, your restraint in the north is appreciated and I will honor our arrangement fully - F DEN stays clear of SWE. My focus is entirely on Belgium and France this year. One observation: Austria sits at 4 centers with units in TYR and ALB - they are well-positioned and growing. If you are looking southward, a coordinated push against Austrian or Turkish positions could be very productive. I have no objection to Russian expansion in the Balkans and would welcome a stronger Russia as a counterweight to Austrian ambitions in central Europe.'}]
