ITA
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, our cooperation continues to serve us both well. I intend to move F ION toward the Aegean this fall to pressure Turkey's position - they're growing strong with GRE and SEV. I'd suggest your F ALB press toward GRE as well. If we coordinate, we can squeeze Turkey's Balkan holdings. My A VEN will hold or move toward TYR to support your northern position if needed. What are your intentions this fall? I want to ensure we don't cross paths in the Adriatic."}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Turkey, I want to be transparent with you - Austria's F ALB is sitting right on your doorstep at GRE, and they bounced you in spring. I'm positioning F ION to potentially support your position if Austria becomes aggressive. However, I need to know your intentions regarding the Aegean and whether you'd welcome Italian support against Austrian encroachment. A coordinated Italy-Turkey front could check Austrian ambitions in the Balkans significantly."}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, I hope our non-aggression holds firm. I'm focused entirely on the eastern Mediterranean this fall - no interest in PIE or your western holdings. Germany looks dangerously strong at 5 centers - have you considered pressing into MUN or BEL? I can offer diplomatic support and potentially distract Austria if that helps your western campaign. Let me know your plans so we can avoid any misunderstandings."}]
--------------
GER
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': "The situation in the west is clear: France is the common enemy. Their A BUR bounced my KIE->RUH move last spring, and they continue to threaten both our positions. I propose we coordinate directly this fall: I will move A HOL->BEL while you support with F NTH->BEL or hold NTH to cover. Alternatively, if you prefer BEL yourself, I need you to support my move into a different center. Either way, France must be contained. What are your intentions for F ENG and F NTH this fall? Let's not waste another season bouncing each other."}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': 'Your A BUR->RUH move last spring was noted - I interpret that as hostile regardless of your framing. I blocked it with KIE->RUH and we bounced. I have no interest in escalating against France if you are willing to respect German territory. My focus is BEL, not French home centers. If you keep A BUR out of RUH and do not contest BEL, I will not push further south or west into French territory. But if you move into RUH again, I will treat it as a declaration of war and coordinate with England accordingly. Your choice.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Our arrangement continues to serve both our interests. I note you hold SWE and are pushing south toward the Balkans - I have no objection to your expansion in that direction. My focus remains western: BEL is my target this fall. I ask only that you keep F SWE out of BAL and SKA - I need those waters stable. In return, I will continue to keep Prussia and Silesia quiet. Are you making progress against Turkey or Austria in the south?'}]
--------------
AUT
[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Last spring was a disaster - we both bounced because RUS moved F RUM to BUL at the same time I moved A SER to BUL, and your A GRE held instead of moving. We need to coordinate properly this fall. Here is my proposal: I will move F ALB to GRE (taking it) while you move A GRE to BUL to secure that center. Simultaneously, I move A SER to RUM to contest that center from RUS. You move F SEV to threaten RUS from the east. This gives us both expansion and puts RUS on the defensive. I need you to confirm A GRE vacates to BUL this turn - that is the critical piece. What say you?'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'RUS, the situation in the Balkans is becoming dangerous for both of us. Turkey now has F SEV and A ARM - they are clearly building against you, not me. I propose we coordinate: I will move A SER to support your F RUM holding in place, keeping RUM in your hands, while you use your northern forces to pressure Turkey. In exchange, I ask that you acknowledge BUL as my sphere of influence going forward. A stable Balkan arrangement benefits us both far more than fighting over scraps while Turkey grows. What specific moves are you planning this fall?'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, I want to maintain our non-aggression arrangement. My units are focused entirely on the Balkans - F ALB moving south, A SER moving toward BUL/RUM. A VIE will move to GAL or BOH, nowhere near you. I ask only that you keep A VEN away from TRI and F ION away from ADR. Turkey is the growing threat in the south - F SEV plus A ARM is a dangerous combination. We should both be watching them carefully. Are you open to coordinating against Turkish expansion in the Mediterranean?'}]
--------------
RUS
[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Turkey, your aggression has cost us both. You seized SEV with false pretenses and now occupy my home center. I am not interested in further negotiation unless you immediately withdraw F SEV back to BLA. If you refuse, I will dedicate every resource to your destruction - I will coordinate with Austria and Italy to dismember you from multiple directions. You have one chance to reverse course. Withdraw from SEV and we can discuss a new arrangement. Otherwise, this is war to the end.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, Turkey has seized Sevastopol - my home center. I know you have been playing both sides, but consider this: Turkey is now the dominant Balkan power with GRE, CON, ANK, SMY, and SEV. They will turn on you next. I propose we coordinate: I will push A UKR toward SEV to retake it, and F RUM can support or move to BUL. If you move A SER to BUL or support my move there, we split the Balkans and contain Turkey together. What do you say? Specific proposal: I take BUL with F RUM, you hold SER and we both pressure Turkey. This is in both our interests.'}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': 'Germany, the situation in the east has become dangerous - Turkey has seized Sevastopol and is growing rapidly. I need to focus south to contain them. I have no designs on your territory and ask only that you continue to hold DEN and not threaten SWE. In return, I will stay out of your affairs entirely and we can maintain our friendly understanding. England is also hostile to me - if you have any leverage over them, a word in my favor would be appreciated. Russia and Germany have no conflict of interest.'}]
--------------
ENG
[{'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "The BEL situation last spring was a mess - both our moves bounced and France slipped away with nothing lost. This fall I want to coordinate properly: I'll move F ENG to BEL, and I need you to support that move with A HOL (A HOL S F ENG - BEL). That guarantees Belgium falls to me. In exchange, I'll support your F DEN into whatever position you need, and I'm happy to discuss HOL remaining firmly in your hands long-term. France is the common threat here - they have 5 centers and are growing. Let's lock down BEL together and then turn our attention to containing France."}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, I think we've been dancing around each other too long. You have 5 centers, I have 4 - we're both in a strong position but neither of us can afford to keep bouncing in BEL while Germany consolidates. I'm willing to discuss a genuine partition: BEL goes to England, and I'll support your position against Germany in RUH or elsewhere. Germany at 5 centers with a fleet in DEN is a real threat to both of us. What would it take to get your A BUR pointed at Germany rather than BEL this fall?"}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, I want to clear the air after last spring's tensions. I have no designs on STP - my fleet is repositioning to NTH for western purposes, not northern aggression. You have SWE and RUM secured, which is excellent. I'd like to propose a quiet northern understanding: I stay out of your Baltic sphere, you stay out of NWY. Germany's growth to 5 centers concerns me - are you watching them carefully? A coordinated Anglo-Russian pressure on Germany could be mutually beneficial."}]
--------------
FRA
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'My friend, the situation is developing well for both of us. Germany sits at 5 centers with HOL, DEN, BER, KIE, MUN — they are the dominant land power and a threat to us both. I propose we coordinate against Germany this fall: I will move A BUR into MUN while you press from the north. My F MAO can threaten the Atlantic or support as needed. If we crack Germany open now, we both benefit enormously. What are your intentions this fall? I want to ensure we are not working at cross-purposes.'}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': 'Germany, I want to be transparent with you: England is pressuring me to join an anti-German coalition. I have no interest in this — France and Germany have more to gain from cooperation than conflict. However, I need something concrete from you to justify resisting English pressure. I propose: I move A BUR to MUN this fall as a show of... actually, let me be direct — I want a formal non-aggression pact through 1904 and German support for French claims on BEL. In return, France will not threaten KIE or HOL. What can you offer?'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, Germany has 5 centers and is the strongest land power on the board. I am considering moving A BUR to MUN this fall to check their growth. If you can press from the south — A VEN toward TYR or TRI — we could squeeze Germany and Austria simultaneously. This is the moment to act while they are not yet dominant. What are your plans this fall? I want to coordinate so our moves complement each other.'}]
--------------
TUR
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, I must be direct with you. Last spring I held GRE rather than moving to BUL as discussed - I saw your F ALB positioned to walk into GRE the moment I vacated, which would have given you two centers (GRE+RUM) while I gained only one. I hope you understand my caution. That said, I remain interested in coordinating against Russia. This fall, I propose: F SEV (which I now hold) moves to RUM to take that center, A GRE moves to BUL to secure it, and A ARM holds or supports. I am NOT asking you to vacate SER or ALB - simply hold your current positions and let me expand north against Russia. In return, I will not contest SER or any Austrian Balkan holdings. Russia is the common threat. Can we agree on this division: BUL and RUM for Turkey, SER and any northern gains for Austria?'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, you now see that I have taken SEV with my fleet - this was a direct response to your aggressive positioning with F RUM threatening my Black Sea access. I am willing to negotiate a settlement rather than escalate. If you withdraw F RUM to BUL or another neutral position and acknowledge Turkish control of SEV, I will consider halting further advances. However, if you attempt to retake SEV by force, I will coordinate with Austria for a full assault on your southern holdings. The choice is yours - peaceful coexistence with adjusted borders, or war on two fronts.'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy, our non-aggression pact continues to serve us both well. I now hold SEV and am positioned to push into RUM and BUL this fall. Austria is becoming dangerously large with 4 centers - I notice their fleet in ALB threatens both of us in the Adriatic/Ionian sphere. I propose we both watch Austria carefully. If Austria moves aggressively toward either of us, we should coordinate a response. For now, I intend to focus entirely on Russia and the Balkans - I have no designs on ION or any Italian sphere. Can you confirm you will keep F ION away from AEG and EAS? I want to ensure we don't accidentally clash."}]
INFO:main:Negotiation sub-round 2/2
