RUS
[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Turkey, you hold SEV with your fleet and ARM with your army - but look at the board. Italy has TRI and AEG, Austria is weakened with only 3 centers, and you are overextended. I have F RUM and A UKR positioned directly against you. This war benefits neither of us while others grow fat. I propose a ceasefire: you return SEV to me, I recognize your hold on GRE and BLA, and we both turn our attention to more productive targets. If you refuse, I will spend every resource grinding you down while Italy takes the Aegean from you. The choice is yours.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, the situation is clear: Turkey holds SEV and threatens both of us from the Black Sea. I am moving A UKR to SEV and F RUM to BUL this turn. I need you to stay out of BUL - if you move A SER to BUL we bounce each other and Turkey wins. Instead, move A SER to support my F RUM into BUL, or move A GAL to support A UKR into SEV. Help me retake SEV and I will support your push into GRE. We can divide the Balkans: BUL for me, GRE for you. Italy is eating your home centers - we need to coordinate or both lose.'}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': 'Germany, I am keeping F SWE out of BAL as promised. My focus is entirely on the Turkish threat in the south - I need to retake SEV. I have no designs on your territory and ask only that you continue your westward focus. France has MUN and is growing dangerously - that should concern you more than anything I am doing. Consider whether England or France is the greater threat to your position, and act accordingly. I remain your friend in the north.'}]
--------------
GER
[{'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': 'France, let us be direct: you hold MUN, one of my home centers, and that is an intolerable situation that will eventually force my hand against you. However, I have no desire for a two-front war while England sits fat with 5 centers. I propose a practical arrangement: you return MUN to German control this spring, and in exchange I will actively support French expansion westward against England - specifically, I will not contest BEL and will coordinate to pressure England from the east while you push from the south. A MUN in French hands is a permanent provocation; a France expanding into BEL and beyond is a useful partner. What say you?'}, {'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'England, your position is strong but you are surrounded by rivals who will eventually unite against you. I am willing to coordinate against France - they hold MUN (my home center) and are clearly the most dangerous continental power right now with 6 centers. If you support pressure on France from the west while I reclaim MUN from the east, we can both benefit. I propose we discuss a formal partition of French gains. What are your thoughts on joint action against France this season?'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, our friendly arrangement continues to serve us both well. I intend to keep DEN stable and have no designs on SWE - the north is yours. My focus is entirely on reclaiming MUN from France and dealing with England's growing naval dominance. I would appreciate your continued non-interference in my western affairs, and in return I remain committed to keeping Prussia and Silesia quiet. The real threats to both of us are the naval powers - England in the north and Turkey in the south. Let us both focus on those threats."}]
--------------
TUR
[{'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, let us be direct: you hold F RUM and A UKR, I hold F SEV and A ARM. A direct clash benefits neither of us while Austria and Italy circle like vultures. I propose a ceasefire: F SEV stays in SEV, F RUM stays in RUM, no attacks this turn. In exchange, I will not push into BLA or threaten your northern position. We both have more dangerous enemies to worry about - Austria is expanding aggressively and Italy has taken Trieste. Let us stabilize the Black Sea region and focus our energies elsewhere. Respond with your intentions.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, the situation has evolved. I hold GRE with A GRE and have no intention of gifting it to you - that was never a realistic offer. However, I am willing to cooperate against Russia, who threatens us both. My F SEV can push to RUM this turn if you coordinate A SER to support or move elsewhere constructively. I will move A GRE to BUL, securing that center for Turkey. You can have Serbia and focus on Galicia against Russia. This is a better arrangement than fighting over GRE while Russia consolidates. What say you?'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy, your F AEG sits adjacent to my home centers and I note you have taken Trieste and expanded significantly. I want to maintain our non-aggression understanding - your fleet in AEG makes me nervous. Can you confirm F AEG will not move to CON or EAS this turn? In return, I have no designs on ION or your western Mediterranean position. We should both be watching Austria's rapid expansion - they now hold SER and are pressing toward the Balkans aggressively. A coordinated approach to limit Austrian growth serves us both."}]
--------------
ITA
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Excellent work last season - I successfully moved F ION to AEG as promised, and we now have a strong pincer position against Turkey. My F AEG can move to GRE or CON this spring, while your F ALB can support or advance. I propose: F AEG moves to GRE (taking it from Turkey), while A TRI moves to SER or holds to consolidate. This gives us both gains - GRE for me, and you secure your Balkan position. Turkey is weakened with F SEV threatening Russia - now is the moment to strike. What are your intended moves this spring?'}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'I must be honest with you - Austria pressured me heavily and I ended up moving to AEG last season. I regret this breach of our agreement. However, I have no hostile intentions toward Turkey - my focus remains on the western Mediterranean. I propose we reset: I will not move F AEG to GRE or CON this spring if you agree to keep A GRE away from ALB and maintain our non-aggression. Austria is the real threat to both of us in the Balkans. Let us not fight each other while Austria grows.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, I believe we have a common interest in checking both Austria and Turkey. Austria holds SER and threatens the Balkans while Turkey has seized SEV from you. I am positioned in AEG and can threaten CON or GRE. If you push F RUM toward BUL and I move F AEG to CON, we can squeeze Turkey significantly. Meanwhile, Austria's F ALB and A SER are exposed if you press from GAL. I am open to coordinating a joint strategy against our mutual rivals - what are your intentions this spring?"}]
--------------
ENG
[{'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, last fall worked out well - you took MUN, I took BEL, and Germany is squeezed. I want to press this advantage together. I propose: I move F BEL to HOL (taking it from Germany) while you hold or advance from MUN toward BER or KIE. Germany is at 4 centers now and vulnerable - if we coordinate, we can strip them further. F ENG can support F BEL into HOL. What are your intentions this spring? I need to know if you're pressing Germany from MUN so I can coordinate my western moves accordingly."}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "Germany, I want to be direct with you: France has taken MUN and is threatening your heartland. I have no interest in destroying you - a weakened Germany serves France more than it serves England. I propose we stabilize: I will not move F BEL to HOL this turn if you commit A KIE to support A HOL holding, keeping your western flank secure. In return, I need you to acknowledge BEL as English and stop contesting it. France is your real enemy right now - let's not fight each other while they pick your bones. What can you offer me to make this arrangement worthwhile?"}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, I've maintained our northern non-aggression understanding and have no designs on your Baltic position. I'm focused entirely on western Europe - France and Germany are my concerns. I'd appreciate knowing your intentions regarding Scandinavia - specifically whether F SWE and A FIN are staying put or moving. Norway is mine and I intend to keep it; as long as you respect that, I see no conflict between us. Are you open to a formal non-aggression pact covering the north?"}]
--------------
AUT
[{'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'The situation is clear: Turkey has broken every agreement and is growing dangerously with 5 centers. I have A SER, F ALB, and A GAL. I propose we coordinate directly this turn: F ALB moves to GRE (taking it from Turkey), A SER moves to BUL (contesting that center), and A GAL holds or moves to RUM. Your F AEG is perfectly positioned to support F ALB into GRE or to threaten Turkish positions in the Aegean. If you move F AEG to support F ALB->GRE, we guarantee I take Greece this turn. In return, I will support your position in TRI and stay out of your Adriatic sphere. Turkey must be contained now before they dominate the south. What specific moves are you planning this turn?'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, let's be direct: we are both threatened by Turkey's rapid expansion to 5 centers with SEV, GRE, and now ARM. I propose a temporary alignment against Turkey this turn. I will move A SER toward BUL or GRE to pressure Turkey from the north. If you move F RUM to support pressure on BUL or hold it defensively, we can coordinate to deny Turkey further Balkan gains. I am not moving A GAL against you - I need it for flexibility. In exchange, I ask that F RUM does not move on SER or BUD. Let's agree: you hold RUM defensively, I push south against Turkey. We can settle our own differences after Turkey is contained."}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Turkey, your refusal to honor our agreements in 1902 has made cooperation impossible. You held GRE when you promised to vacate, you took SEV while claiming to coordinate with me. I am done negotiating in good faith with you. Consider this a warning: I will be moving aggressively into the Balkans this turn and I have coordinated with Italy and Russia to contain your expansion. If you want to avoid being squeezed from three directions, you need to offer something concrete - specifically, vacate GRE immediately and agree to a defined sphere that does not include BUL. Otherwise we are at war.'}]
--------------
FRA
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': "Excellent work last season — MUN is ours and Germany is reeling. I now hold MUN with A MUN, GAS with A GAS, and MAO with F MAO. Germany is down to 4 centers and vulnerable. I propose we continue the pressure: I will move A MUN to BER or KIE to strike at Germany's remaining heartland, while you hold BEL and potentially push into HOL. This is the moment to finish Germany off before they recover. What are your intentions this season? I want to coordinate so we don't waste this advantage."}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': 'Germany, I want to be direct with you: France has no interest in destroying you entirely. I took MUN because you were threatening my position, but I am open to a negotiated settlement. If you agree to cede MUN permanently and focus your remaining forces eastward, I will halt my advance and we can establish a stable border. The alternative is continued pressure from both France and England simultaneously, which will end badly for you. Consider this offer carefully — I would rather have a weakened but stable Germany as a buffer than a power vacuum filled by England.'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, Germany is now severely weakened with France holding MUN. This is the moment for both of us to press our advantages. I intend to push deeper into German territory this season. I would encourage you to consider moving through TYR toward VIE or BOH — Austria is also vulnerable with only 3 centers. A coordinated Franco-Italian push against both Germany and Austria would reshape the board dramatically in our favor. What are your plans this season? Let us not let this opportunity pass.'}]
INFO:main:Negotiation sub-round 2/2
