FRA
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': "England, I am fully committed to pressing Germany this season. My plan: A MUN moves to KIE or BER to strike at Germany's remaining home centers, while F MAO holds to maintain Atlantic flexibility. Your move of F BEL to HOL with F ENG support is exactly right — let's execute this simultaneously so Germany cannot concentrate against either of us. If you take HOL and I take KIE or BER, Germany collapses to 2 centers and is effectively finished. Confirm you are moving F BEL to HOL with F ENG support, and I will coordinate my MUN advance accordingly. This is the moment — let's finish it."}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': 'Germany, I have considered your offer, but returning MUN is not something I can do — it would simply restore the threat to my position. However, I am genuinely open to a ceasefire on these terms: I hold A MUN in place this season and do not advance further, and you agree not to attempt to retake MUN. This gives you time to stabilize your eastern position while I focus my attention elsewhere. England is the real long-term threat on this board — they now hold BEL and NWY and are growing fast. A France-Germany understanding against English expansion is more valuable than continued mutual destruction. Think carefully about who your real enemy is.'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, the board is shifting rapidly — Germany is weakened, but England is growing dangerously with 5 centers and a strong fleet position. I intend to press Germany further this season from MUN. I would strongly encourage you to move through TYR toward BOH or VIE — Austria is at only 3 centers and vulnerable, and a coordinated Franco-Italian advance against both Germany and Austria would give us both significant gains before England becomes unstoppable. Do not let this window close. What specific moves are you planning this season?'}]
--------------
ENG
[{'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, I'm fully committed to pressing Germany this season. My plan: F BEL moves to HOL, supported by F ENG - this takes HOL from Germany and cuts them to 3 centers. I need you to advance A MUN toward KIE or BER to keep Germany pinned and unable to defend HOL. If you move A MUN to KIE and I take HOL, Germany collapses. A GAS can hold or move to support. This is the moment - let's execute together and divide Germany's remaining centers between us. Confirm you're moving A MUN to KIE this turn."}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "Germany, I hear your proposal for joint action against France, and I'm genuinely sympathetic - France at 6 centers is dangerous for everyone. However, I need a concrete gesture of good faith from you: formally acknowledge BEL as English and pull A HOL back from any threat to BEL. In return, I will hold F BEL in place this turn rather than pressing into HOL, giving you breathing room to deal with France from MUN. If you can retake MUN from France, I'll actively support your western flank. But I need your commitment on BEL first - what say you?"}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, I appreciate the stability in the north. I'm moving F BEL toward HOL this season to press Germany - this is purely western business and doesn't affect our arrangement. Norway stays mine, your Baltic and Scandinavian position is untouched. I'd welcome a formal non-aggression pact: you stay out of NWY and NTH, I stay out of SWE, FIN, and the Baltic. This frees us both to focus on our real objectives - you against Turkey and Austria, me against Germany and France. Agreed?"}]
--------------
ITA
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, I am fully committed to our coordinated strike against Turkey this spring. My F AEG will move to GRE, taking it from Turkey. I need you to move F ALB to support F AEG into GRE to guarantee the capture - this is the critical move. A SER can then advance to BUL in the fall once GRE is secured. A TRI will hold to protect our shared border. This gives me GRE and positions us both for further gains against Turkey. Confirm F ALB supports F AEG into GRE and we have a deal.'}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Turkey, I hear your concerns and I want to be direct: I am moving F AEG to GRE this spring. Austria has already committed F ALB to take GRE and I cannot stop that momentum - better I take it than Austria, as I am a more reasonable neighbor. However, I have absolutely no designs on CON or SMY - those are yours. I propose we immediately establish a firm line: GRE becomes Italian, you keep CON, SMY, ANK, SEV, and we coordinate against Austria's Balkan expansion together. A GRE can retreat to ALB or BUL - do not waste it fighting me when Austria is the real threat."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, I am moving F AEG to GRE this spring in coordination with Austria against Turkey. However, I want you to know my long-term interests align more with Russia than Austria - Austria is growing dangerously with SER, VIE, BUD, and GAL. Once Turkey is contained, Austria becomes the primary threat to both of us. I suggest you use F RUM to press toward BUL or CON to claim Turkish territory before Austria does - do not let Austria dominate the Balkans. I will keep A TRI positioned to check Austrian ambitions from the west. Let us both expand at Turkey's expense while watching Austria carefully."}]
--------------
TUR
[{'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, I hear your proposal but returning SEV is off the table - I took it fairly and it is mine. However, I am genuinely open to a ceasefire on current positions: F SEV stays in SEV, F RUM stays in RUM, no attacks this turn. I will move A GRE to BUL this turn, not toward you. A ARM will hold or reposition away from your territory. Austria is threatening both of us and Italy is expanding into the Aegean. A RUS-TUR war right now only benefits Austria and Italy. Let us hold our current lines and reassess next season. I am moving defensively this turn - I hope you will do the same.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, your threats are noted but consider the reality: you have 3 centers, I have 5, and Russia has 5. If you spend your energy fighting me over GRE, Russia will roll over Galicia and Italy will take more of your home centers. I am moving A GRE to BUL this turn - you can have GRE if F ALB moves there, I will not contest it. In exchange, I need you to leave RUM to me and focus your A SER northward against Russia. This is the only arrangement that benefits us both. Fighting each other while Russia and Italy grow is suicide for Austria.'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, I appreciate your honesty about AEG. I accept your proposal: keep F AEG out of CON and GRE this turn, and I will keep A GRE away from ALB. I am moving A GRE to BUL this turn, which actually opens GRE - I trust you will not exploit this. Austria is threatening war against me and claims you are coordinating with them - I hope this is not true. Austria with 3 centers is not a threat worth allying with against a 5-center Turkey. We both benefit from Austrian weakness. Confirm F AEG holds or moves west, and our non-aggression stands.'}]
--------------
GER
[{'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, your offer to 'cede MUN permanently' in exchange for my submission is laughable - you are asking me to accept the permanent loss of my home center while you grow fat. I will not. My orders this spring are A KIE -> MUN to retake what is mine. If you resist, you will face pressure from both east and west simultaneously. If you withdraw A MUN voluntarily, I will consider you a partner rather than an enemy and we can discuss a genuine arrangement against England. The choice is yours: return MUN peacefully and we negotiate, or fight me for it and face the consequences."}, {'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'England, I appreciate your directness. I accept that BEL is yours for now - I have no units positioned to contest it this season. My focus is entirely on reclaiming MUN from France. I propose this: you pressure France from the west with F BEL threatening BUR, while I push A KIE -> MUN from the east. A France squeezed from both sides cannot hold MUN. In return, I commit A HOL to hold and will not threaten BEL. This is a genuine offer - France with 6 centers is the dominant continental power and must be cut down. Let us act together this season.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, your message is well received and I remain committed to our northern arrangement. France is indeed the immediate threat - they hold MUN and are growing dangerously. I am moving to reclaim MUN this spring. I ask only that you continue your southern focus and keep SWE stable. If France continues to expand, they will eventually threaten both of us - a dominant France is no friend to Russia either. Stay the course in the south against Turkey, and I will handle the western front.'}]
--------------
RUS
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, I am moving F RUM to BUL and A UKR to SEV this turn. I need you to NOT move A SER to BUL - if we both go there we bounce and Turkey wins. Instead, move A GAL to support A UKR into SEV, or move A SER to GRE to pressure Turkey from the south. If you support my F RUM into BUL, I will support your push into GRE next turn. This is the coordinated strike we need: I take BUL, you take GRE, Turkey is squeezed from both sides. Do not move into BUL - that is my sphere this turn.'}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Turkey, your ceasefire proposal is noted but insufficient. You seized SEV - my home center - through treachery. A ceasefire that leaves you in SEV is no ceasefire at all. Return SEV and I will halt my advance; otherwise my F RUM moves to BUL and A UKR presses toward SEV. Italy is already in AEG threatening your southern flank. You are overextended. The rational choice is to return what you took and stabilize - or face a two-front war with Russia and Italy simultaneously while Austria presses from the north.'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, your proposal aligns with my intentions. I am moving F RUM to BUL and A UKR toward SEV this turn. If you move F AEG to CON, we create a devastating pincer on Turkey - they cannot defend everywhere. I support this coordination fully. On Austria: they are weakened at 3 centers and you already hold TRI. Let us focus on Turkey first, then reassess Austria. Confirm you are moving F AEG to CON and we have a deal.'}]
--------------
AUT
[{'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy, I need to be direct with you: I cannot let you take GRE - that is my target this turn. F ALB moves to GRE, supported by A SER. Your F AEG should move to CON or SMY to threaten Turkey's heartland instead - that is far more valuable than GRE and opens Turkey's home centers to you. If you move F AEG to GRE we will bounce each other and Turkey survives unscathed. Move F AEG to CON this turn, I take GRE, and together we split Turkey's territory. A TRI should hold or move to ALB to support my fleet if needed. This is the coordinated strike that actually works - you get CON, I get GRE, Turkey collapses."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, I hear your proposal but I cannot support F RUM into BUL - I need A SER free to move to GRE or BUL myself. Here is what I can offer: A GAL will NOT move against you this turn - I give you that guarantee. Move F RUM to BUL if you wish, and I will move A SER to GRE (not BUL), so we do not bounce. You get BUL, I get GRE, Turkey loses both. F ALB supports A SER into GRE. This is the clean division that actually works: BUL for Russia, GRE for Austria. Confirm you are moving F RUM to BUL and not to SER or BUD, and we have a deal.'}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Turkey, your offer is too little too late. You want A GRE to BUL - which means you keep BUL and I get nothing while you consolidate. I am moving F ALB to GRE this turn regardless. If A GRE vacates to BUL as you claim, F ALB walks in uncontested and we avoid conflict. If you hold GRE, we bounce and you face coordinated pressure from Italy's F AEG and my forces next turn. The choice is yours: vacate GRE now and we can discuss a working arrangement, or hold and face a two-front war you cannot win."}]
