[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'England, here is my concrete proposal for this season: I will move A KIE -> BER to retake my home center, supported by F BAL -> BER. A MUN holds to block any French advance from BUR. I need you to move F HOL -> BEL or at minimum hold F HOL in place to prevent France from reinforcing BER via the west. If you hold F HOL and F NTH defensively, France cannot safely move A BUR east without exposing themselves. In return, I acknowledge BEL as yours once France is weakened - I have no interest in contesting it. France at 6 centers is the existential threat to both of us. Commit to holding F HOL and F NTH defensively this turn and we have a deal.'}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': 'France, your ceasefire terms are unacceptable - you keep BER while I disarm? That is not a ceasefire, that is surrender. Here is my counter: you withdraw A BER to SIL this turn, I hold A MUN and A KIE in place, and we establish a genuine ceasefire with the 1904 borders as the baseline. If you refuse, I am moving A KIE -> BER with F BAL support this very turn. England is already coordinating with me against you - do not test whether I am bluffing. A negotiated withdrawal from BER is your best option; the alternative is a two-front war you cannot win while Italy presses from the south.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, confirmed - our northern arrangement holds and I have no designs on SWE or PRU. My moves this turn are entirely focused westward: retaking BER from France. I would ask one additional favor - if you can move any unit toward WAR or SIL to create pressure on France's eastern flank, it would help enormously. Even a feint toward SIL would force France to worry about their rear. In return, I will actively support your position in Scandinavia and stay completely out of your eastern affairs. Germany and Russia have no conflict of interest - France is the common threat growing too powerful in the west."}]
