[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': "Confirmed — the division stands: KIE and DEN for England, MUN for France. My orders this spring: A BER moves to KIE, A BUR moves to MUN. Your F HOL to KIE will either support my move or take it if I bounce — either way Germany loses KIE. Push F NTH to DEN simultaneously to lock in the northern centers. Germany is finished if we execute cleanly. After this, let's discuss the broader board — Italy at 6 centers and Russia at 6 are the next concerns."}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "Germany, I appreciate the offer but the strategic reality is clear: England is moving F HOL to KIE and F NTH to DEN this very turn. I cannot withdraw from BER when England is already advancing — that would simply hand your centers to them instead of creating any stability. If you want to survive, your only option is to coordinate with me against England: hold A MUN, move A KIE to DEN to block England's F NTH, and let F BAL contest HOL. I will hold A BER and A BUR in place this turn as a gesture of good faith. England is the real threat to both of us."}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, I am moving to eliminate Germany this spring — A BER to KIE, A BUR to MUN. Once Germany falls, France will be at 8 centers and we must coordinate carefully. I strongly urge you to press Austria hard into BUD and SER — do not let Russia absorb those centers. Russia at 6 centers with a fleet in RUM and armies threatening the Balkans is the emerging danger. If you take BUD and SER while I consolidate Germany, we can present a united front against Russian expansion. What are your specific moves this spring?'}]
